{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17647063","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17647063"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:39:20+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:39:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18224"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18224","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18224"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0,0,0,1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10938"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79207"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10938","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10938"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18224"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64559"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"10214"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25423"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25426"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79207","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79207"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following correctly describes the pathophysiology of osteoporosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Excessive calcium deposition in bone matrix","Increased osteoblast activity leading to excessive bone formation","Decreased osteoclast activity resulting in bone accumulation","Increased bone density due to enhanced mineralisation","Imbalance between bone resorption and formation favouring resorption"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImbalance between bone resorption and formation favouring resorption\u003C/strong\u003E is the correct description of the pathophysiology of osteoporosis. In osteoporosis, there is an imbalance between the activity of osteoclasts, which resorb bone, and osteoblasts, which form bone. This imbalance leads to a net loss of bone mass and deterioration of bone microarchitecture, increasing the risk of fractures.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased osteoblast activity\u003C/strong\u003E would lead to excessive bone formation, which is not characteristic of osteoporosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecreased osteoclast activity\u003C/strong\u003E results in bone accumulation, which is contrary to the bone loss seen in osteoporosis. Osteoclast activity is increased or unopposed in osteoporosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExcessive calcium deposition\u003C/strong\u003E in the bone matrix leads to increased bone density. Osteoporosis is characterised by decreased bone density.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased bone density\u003C/strong\u003E due to enhanced mineralisation is not a feature of osteoporosis. Osteoporosis involves decreased bone density and increased fracture risk due to the imbalance in bone remodelling.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Osteoporosis is characterised by decreased bone mass and deterioration of bone tissue, leading to increased fracture risk.","The imbalance between bone resorption and bone formation is a key factor in the development of osteoporosis.","Osteoclast activity surpasses osteoblast activity, resulting in net bone loss."],"references":["Khurana, I., Khurana, A., \u0026 Kowlgi, N. G. (2019). Textbook of Medical Physiology_-E-book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Clarke B. Normal bone anatomy and physiology. Clin J Am Soc Nephrol. 2008 Nov;3 Suppl 3(Suppl 3):S131-9. doi: 10.2215/CJN.04151206. PMID: 18988698; PMCID: PMC3152283","Florencio-Silva R, Sasso GR, Sasso-Cerri E, Sim\u00f5es MJ, Cerri PS. Biology of Bone Tissue: Structure, Function, and Factors That Influence Bone Cells. Biomed Res Int. 2015;2015:421746. doi: 10.1155/2015/421746. Epub 2015 Jul 13. PMID: 26247020; PMCID: PMC4515490","Cowan PT, Launico MV, Kahai P. Anatomy, Bones. 2024 Apr 21. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30725884","Porter JL, Varacallo M. Osteoporosis. 2023 Aug 4. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 28722930","LeBoff MS, Greenspan SL, Insogna KL, Lewiecki EM, Saag KG, Singer AJ, Siris ES. The clinician\u0027s guide to prevention and treatment of osteoporosis. Osteoporos Int. 2022 Oct;33(10):2049-2102. doi: 10.1007/s00198-021-05900-y. Epub 2022 Apr 28. Erratum in: Osteoporos Int. 2022 Oct;33(10):2243. doi: 10.1007/s00198-022-06479-8. PMID: 35478046; PMCID: PMC9546973"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64559"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18224"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64559","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64559"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-13T17:45:01+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-13T17:45:37+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10938"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79207"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/ap